ant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mowbray","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern; of Norman origin): habitational name from Montbray (Manche). Robert <i>de Mowbray</i> was Earl of Northumbria 1086–95, but was later imprisoned and deposed for rebelling against William II."],"variants":[{"name":"Mulberry","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Cambridgeshire): variant of   Mowbray  .","Irish (Derry): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoilbhearaigh</b> ‘descendant of the devotee of (Saint) <i>Bearach</i>’."]},{"name":"Moubray","meanings":["English: variant of   Mowbray  ."]},{"name":"Mayberry","meanings":["English: most probably an altered form of   Mowbray  . It is also found as   Maybury  , which has the form of an English habitational name. There is a place near Woking in Surrey so called; however, this is not recorded until 1885 and is probably derived from the surname. In England this surname is found mainly in the West Midlands; it has also spread into Wales. In Ireland this form is common in Ulster; MacLysaght records that it was taken there from England in the 17th century."]},{"name":"Memory","meanings":["English: variant of   Mowbray  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Mowbray was born about 1275, his father, William de Mowbray, was 22 and his mother, Helen, was 37. He married Agnes Depden about 1296. He died about 1320, at the age of 47."},"et":{"Abt 1275–Abt 1320":"umbes 1275–umbes 1320","1275–1320":"1275–1320","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","–1293":"–1293","1255–1293":"1255–1293","1240–1293":"1240–1293","Abt 1296":"umbes 1296","about 1280":"umbes 1280","Abt 1293":"umbes 1293","Abt 1320":"umbes 1320","1255":"1255","Abt 1275":"umbes 1275","1320":"1320","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1293":"1293","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1275–Abt 1320":"noin 1275–noin 1320","1275–1320":"1275–1320","1285–Female":"1285–Kuollut","–1293":"–1293","1255–1293":"1255–1293","1240–1293":"1240–1293","Abt 1296":"noin 1296","about 1280":"noin 1280","Abt 1293":"noin 1293","Abt 1320":"noin 1320","1255":"1255","Abt 1275":"noin 1275","1320":"1320","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1293":"1293","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1275–Abt 1320":"environ 1275–environ 1320","1275–1320":"1275–1320","1285–Female":"1285–Décédée","–1293":"–1293","1255–1293":"1255–1293","1240–1293":"1240–1293","Abt 1296":"environ 1296","about 1280":"environ 1280","Abt 1293":"environ 1293","Abt 1320":"environ 1320","1255":"1255","Abt 1275":"environ 1275","1320":"1320","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1293":"1293","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque William de Mowbray est né environ 1275, son père, William de Mowbray, avait 22 ans et sa mère, Helen, avait 37 ans. Il a épousé Agnes Depden environ 1296. Il est décédé environ 1320, à l’âge de 47 ans."},"de":{"Abt 1275–Abt 1320":"um 1275–um 1320","1275–1320":"1275–1320","1285–Female":"1285–Verstorben","–1293":"–12